  "prompt": "What is the most effective study method?",
  "response": "There's no single \"most effective\" study method, as different people learn differently. However, some research-backed techniques include:\n\n1. Active Recall\n- Testing yourself on material\n- Using flashcards\n- Practicing explaining concepts\n\n2. Spaced Repetition\n- Reviewing material at increasing intervals\n- Helps transfer information to long-term memory\n\n3. Pomodoro Technique\n- Study in focused 25-minute intervals\n- Take short breaks between sessions\n- Helps maintain concentration\n\n4. The Feynman Technique\n- Explain concepts in simple language\n- Helps identify gaps in understanding\n\n5. Mind Mapping\n- Visual representation of information\n- Connects ideas and improves comprehension\n\n6. Practice Problems/Mock Exams\n- Simulates real test conditions\n- Identifies weak areas\n\n7. Interleaving\n- Mix different types of problems/subjects\n- Improves overall understanding\n\nThe most effective method varies by individual, so experiment to find what works best for you. Factors like learning style, subject matter, and personal preferences matter.\n\nGeneral tips:\n- Stay consistent\n- Get enough sleep\n- Stay hydrated\n- Create a good study environment\n- Take breaks",
